25|$|In September 1918, a Finnish {{immigrant}} named Olli Kinkkonen was lynched in Duluth, allegedly for dodging {{military service}} in World War I, which the United States had recently entered. Kinkkonen was found dead, tarred and feathered, and {{hanging from a}} tree in Lester Park. Authorities did not pursue murder charges; they claimed that he had committed suicide after <b>the</b> <b>shame</b> <b>of</b> having been tarred and feathered.|$|E
